 Dumfriesshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"WAUCHOPE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from either of two places in Scotland: Wauchopedale in Dumfriesshire or Wauchope in Hobkirk (Roxburghshire). The placename is from Old English <i>wala hop</i> ‘valley of the Welshmen’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ALEXANDER","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"ALEXANDER WAUCHOPE was born about 1330, in Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs Alexander Wauchope."},"et":{"about 1330–":"umbes 1330–Surnud","1332–Female":"1332–Surnud","1355–Female":"1355–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1355":"1355","1332":"1332","1330":"1330","about 1355":"umbes 1355","about 1330":"umbes 1330","Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Langholm, Dumfries, Scotland":"Langholm, Dumfriesshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1330–":"noin 1330–Kuollut","1332–Female":"1332–Kuollut","1355–Female":"1355–Kuollut","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1355":"1355","1332":"1332","1330":"1330","about 1355":"noin 1355","about 1330":"noin 1330","Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Dumfriesshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Langholm, Dumfries, Scotland":"Langholm, Dumfr